@node Main "StIco - The Stereoscopic 'Ico' Program"

StIco is @{"Copyright" link Copyright} 1992-1996 by the @{"author" link Author} (David M. McKinstry).  This version is written for AmigaDOS 2.1 or later, but has certain features that make it act similar to a program running in @{"Windows" link Windows} 3.1 or Windows 95.

StIco (or Stereoscopic Icosahedron) provides stereoscopic views of any of six geometric shapes. It is based on the
@{"X Window" link X} program @{"Ico" link Ico}.  The animation may be permitted to run freely as it does in X Windows, or you may use the cursor keys to make the images undergo real-time rotation about either of two axes. In addition, you may zoom the images by pressing the 'A' key to move the image away from you, or the 'R' key to return it toward you.
The up and down arrows tilt the figure about an horizontal axis, and the left and right arrows produce rotation about a new axis oriented at right angles to the first.  the motion is not likely to be as you expect, as the second axis is only initially oriented near the vertical. It is suggested that you use the Options menu to toggle the 'Free Running' mode off, and practice.  In the Free Running mode, several options are available.

See the Options topic to find out about them.

Click @{"here" link Glasses.brush/main} to see how to use the 3D Glasses to view anaglyph images.

Have Fun!

The Window titled 'Stereoscopic Ico' has the following menus:

	@{"Project" link Project} - The limited project menu

	@{"Geometry" link Geometry} - Description of Geometries generated by StIco

	@{"Options" link Options} - Selection Options for StIco

	@{"Help" link Help} - Leads you to this file

	In addition, if you have not already done so, you should read the following topics:

	@{"Copyright" link Copyright} - Copyright and restrictions

	@{"3D Glasses" link Glasses} - Source for 3D glasses

	@{"Quit" link Quit} - Quitting StIco.guide or StIco

@endnode



@node Copyright "About the copyright"



Note that this program is freeware and may be freely distributed via electronic media or any other transfer method that does not result in any profit to the distributor other than reasonable recovery of expenses.  Of course, the Fred Fish collection is considered to be in this category.  Of course, using this software to demonstrate Amigas or Amiga-related equipment is not distributing the software for profit, and may be done without restrictions.  Giving it away requires the meeting of the restrictions mentioned below.


The following restriction applies.  The help files StIco.guide, and any other files that came with StIcoV16.lha must be included.  Otherwise, the distributor is in violation of the intent of this copyright.


The easiest way to assure that these restrictions are met is to only transfer the archive StIcoV16.lha.  In principle, this should be the file from which you obtained this program and its supporting files.


The author makes no claims as the suitability or reliablity of this software, and is in no way responsible for any damages that the user may feel have occurred as a result of its use.

Nevertheless, the @{"author" link author} anticipates no problems with the use of this software, but would appreciate receiving @{"bug reports" link bug} on any difficulties encountered in conjunction with its use.



@endnode

@node author "About the Author"

I received my Ph.D. from the University of Nevada at Reno in 1972.  My doctoral research was in the area of surface physics, using the tools of field-ion microscopy.  After a year of post-doctoral research and teaching at U.N.R., I went to Michigan, where I taught at Southwestern Michigan College for ten years.

Since I'm from Washington State, and my wife is from California, we wanted to get back to the West Coast.  I'm currently a professor of physis at Eastern Washington University, where I've been teaching since 1983.

Although our three children are all grown and have left home, my wife (Donna) and I live in Cheney, Washington.  Donna and I can occasionally be found at science fiction conventions.  Donna will be taking a job in Amburg, German this October, so we will be having a long-distance marriage for a while.  I will be traveling to Germany whenever I have a break from my classes.  Of course, I can do software development as well in Germany as I can here.

I've been writing software for use in physics education since 1978, when I got my first personal computer.  Most of it has just been for my own use within the classroom.  I was thrilled by the power of the Amiga when it came out in 1985, and have been using an Amiga ever since.  It was the first personal computer that had the color capability to permit the display of red-blue anaglyph stereoscopic images, and I've been working with stereoscopic animations since 1987.  The first program in which I used this technique was 'Crystal Lattices'.  It was released on BIX in 1988, and is in the Fred Fish collection. Although I've written other software for the Amiga as well, working with stereoscopic imaging has occupied the greater part of my time.

Current development includes 'FandP' (Fields and Potentials).  This should be released within the next year, and will be available for both the Amiga, and a 'PC' running Windows 3.1 or Windows 95.

Please contact @{"me" link bug} if you are an educator interested in beta testing FandP.


@endnode




@node Help "Program description"

Selecting 'Program Description' from the 'Help' menu, using Right-Amiga D, or double clicking on the 'StIco.guide' icon in the directory in which StIco is located will bring up this AmigaGuide help file.
@endnode


@node Glasses "3D Glasses"


Any stereoscopic imaging technique requires providing two separate images.  That is, one image for each eye.  The images for this program are calculated in real-time, using a technique discussed by me (the author of this program) in the article "3-D Amiga Images For the Physics Classroom" in Computers in Physics SEP/OCT 1988.

Two techniques are especially effective for permitting the viewer to merge the two images into a single stereoscopic view on a personal computer.  Using liquid crystal shutter glasses permits the viewing of full color stereoscopic images.  For one-sixtieth of a second the lens over the left eye is opaque, while on the monitor the image for the right eye is displayed.  During the next sixtieth of a second, the lens over the right eye is made opaque while the image for the left eye is being displayed.  There are two problems associated with this technique.  The first is that color images tend to take longer to generate.  This makes it more difficult to do real-time generation of colored stereoscopic images.  The second is that this technique requires double buffering of the two images, and the ability to detect a vertical blanking interrupt.  To my knowledge, the Windows software does not provide this capability to the programmer.  If anyone knows otherwise, please let know where I can find the documentation.  This technique has been used successfully on the Amiga and the Atari which do permit both double buffering and the detection of the vertical blanking interrupt.  In fact, I have done this in 1024 x 768 resolution with 256 colors on my Amiga, using GfxBase's GDA-1 graphics card.  That card does provide a vertical blanking interrupt and double buffering.  However, I have not animated those images.

The second successful approach is to use Anaglyph Glasses to filter the images so that each eye can only see the image intended for it.  For example, this program displays the image for the left eye as red.  Viewing that image with the blue filter over the right eye will make the left eye's image invisible.  Similary, the right eye's image is drawn blue, so that it is visible through the blue filter, but not the red filter over the left eye.  Although not as satisfying as color images, the cost is much more affordable.  Furthermore, drawing wire frame images is accomplished much more rapidly.

The source I've used for the 3D glasses is:

The 3-D Zone                        Phone  (213) 662-3831
P.O. Box 741159
L.A., CA  90004

Another source is:

Reel 3-D Enterprises, Inc.			Phone	(310) 837-2368
P.O. Box 2368
Culver City, CA 90231

You may want to phone or write these sources for current pricing.

@endnode

@node Ico "About Ico"


Following is the Copyright notice that comes with the source code for Ico:

"Copyright 1987 by Digital Equipment Corporation, Maynard, Massachusetts, and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Cambridge, Massachusettes.


                    All Rights Reserved

Permission to use, copy, modify, and distribute this software and its documentation for any purpose without fee is hereby granted, provided that the above copyright notice appear in all copies and that both that copyright notice and this permission notice appear in supporting documentation, and the names of Digital or MIT not be used in advertising or publicity pertaining to distribution of the software without specific, written prior permission.

DIGITAL DISCLAIMS ALL WARRANTIES WITH REGARD TO THIS SOFTWARE, INCLUDING ALL IMPLIED WARRANTIES OF MECHANTABILITY AND FITNESS, IN NO EVENT SHALL DIGITAL BE LIABLE FOR ANY SPECIAL, INDIRECT OR CONSEQUENTIAL DAMAGES OR ANY DAMAGES WHATSOEVER RESULTING FROM LOSS OF USE, DATA OR PROFITS, WHETHER IN ACTION OR CONTRACT, NEGLIGENCE OR OTHER TORTIOUS ACTION, ARISING OUT OF OR IN CONNECTION WITH THE USE OR PERFORMANCE OF THIS SOFTWARE."


The author of STICO has not directly copied or modified the code for this release, as it had been written from scratch for @{"Windows 3.1" link Windows} and involves stereoscopic imaging techniques independently developed by the author on the Amiga.  This port has been made to the Amiga, as the Amiga has been my favorite computer, since I first got one in 1985.  Nevertheless, the ideas for STICO come from ICO, and the above copyright notice is included to acknowledge that influence.  Furthermore, this author makes the same disclaimers as does DIGITAL in the above statement.

Note that there are a number of features present with Ico that do not exist with StIco.  These include double buffering (which the author of StIco has as yet been unable to accomplish with Windows, and has been purposely been kept out of the Amiga Version to keep it consistent), Solid faces (which are impractical with the red/blue glasses used for the stereoscopic techniques), and a variety of other features that may or might not be included at a later date.  Of course, the 'Bucky Ball'  does not exist as a part of Ico, as the structure was not discovered at the time that Ico was written.  Of course, the volley ball has been around, and it is in many ways similar to the Bucky Ball.

@endnode

@node X "About X Windows"

This brief note is provided for anyone not familiar with the X Window System. The X Window System (or X) is a graphical environment that is similar in many respects to that provided by the Amiga and its Intuition, and more recently MS-DOS Windows.  However X has been available for a number of years as a part of systems running UNIX.  Within the last 5 years, X has been ported from UNIX to other environments including the Amiga and DOS machines.  Of course, X runs on any implementation of a complete UNIX system, including LINUX.

@endnode

@node Quit "Quitting StIco"

To Quit StIco.guide, use the left mouse button to click on the close gadget in the upper-left corner of the window, or pull down the project menu to select quit, or use Right-Amiga Q.

To Quit StIco with the Stereoscopic Ico Window active, you may also use the close gadget (on the StIco window), right-Amiga Q, or Quit from the project menu.

@endnode

@node Project "Project"

Currently there are only two active selections under the Project Menu.  These are 'About StIco', which simply displays the copyright information, and 'Quit', which may be used to terminate the Project.  At a later time the possibility of creating, saving and loading stereoscopic object files 'may' be implemented.
@endnode

@node Windows "MicroSoft Windows"

Currently, Windows 95 is the latest release of Microsoft's windowing program.  It provides most of the features that have been available on the Amiga for the past 10 to 11 years.  'StIco' was developed on Windows 3.1, and Windows 95 overcomes most of the objections the author had to Windows 3.1.
@endnode

@node Geometry "Geometries"

	StIco Generates the following Geometries:

	@{"Cube" link Cube}

	@{"Octahedron" link Octahedron}

	@{"Pyramid" link Pyramid}

	@{"Plane" link Plane}

	@{"Icosahedron" link Icosahedron}

	@{"Bucky Ball" link Bucky Ball}

After having read the descriptions of the options, select the desired option from the Options Menu, and select the geometry you wish to view from the Geometry Menu.  Note that changes of the geometry selected, or any of the options may be made 'on the fly'.


@endnode

@node Cube "Cube"

The cube is a simple geometric structure consisting of six square faces joined at right angles to one another.  Thus, twelve line segments join eight corners to form the cube.

@endnode

@node Octahedron "Octahedron"

The octahedron is formed by joining the corners of a square to a pair of points directly above and below the center of the square.  In this example, the distance of these points above and below the square is equal to the length of the sides of the square.  A total of twelve line segments join 6 vertices.  Thus, the octahedron consists of eight triangular faces (hence the name octahedron)

@endnode

@node Pyramid "Pyramid"

A pyramid is formed by joining the four corners of a square to a point directly above (or below) the center of that square.  The pyramid might be simply considered only the upper half of the Octahedron.  A total of eight line segments join five vertices.  Thus, the pyramid consists of five faces.  These consist of a square base and four triangles.

@endnode

@node Plane "Plane"

The plane shown here is simply a square.  The only reason such a two-dimensional object is being included in this program is that it was included in the X Windows program Ico, and is being rotated through three-dimensional space.

@endnode

@node Icosahedron "Icosahedron"


The icosohedron (hence the name for the X Windows program Ico) is a more complex three dimensional geometry.  The icosohedron (also known as a dodecahedron) consists of a total of thirty line segments used to form twenty faces (hence the name dodecahedron).  Each of these faces is a triangle.

@endnode

@node Bucky Ball "Buckminster Fullerine"

The Bucky Ball (the geometric shape for Buckminster Fullerine) consists of a number of pentagons and hexagons joined into a three-dimensional object.  This program starts with a pentagon having sides of specified length, attaches five hexagons to it, and folds them down until their adjacent edges overlap.  The folding angle is just acos[tan(3pi/10)/tan(pi/3)].  A second set of five hexagons is attached to the first set at their outer edges and tilted down again.  These are tilted from the original orientation of the first pentagon, until the distance between the right-most vertex of each hexagon is the same distance from the left-most vertex of the hexagon on its right as the length of the side of each hexagon or pentagon.  All tilt angles after this point are either the same, or supplementary or complementary to angles already determined.
@endnode

@node Options "Options"


There are eight options available under the Options menu.  All except Eye Spacing may be toggled on or off.  Some of them are mutually exclusive.

These options are:

	@{"Free Running" link FREE_RUNNING}

	@{"Show Walls" link SHOW_WALLS}

	@{"Constant Rate" link CONSTANT_RATE}

	@{"Sound" link SOUND}

	@{"Reverse Video" link REVERSE_VIDEO}

	@{"Other Palette" link OTHER_PALETTE}

	@{"Workbench Colors" link WORKBENCH_COLORS}

	@{"Eye Spacing" link Eyes}

When an option is selected, there is a check mark beside it in the menu.  The defaults are 'Free Running' on, 'Show Walls' off, 'Constant Rate' on, 'Sound' on, 'Reverse Video' off, and 'Other Palette' off.

In addition, timing is continually conducted during the animations, and a display of the latest results may be obtained by pressing the 'U' key to
@{"Update Timing" link UPDATE_TIMING}.

@endnode


@node Free_Running "Free Running"

When the Free Running option is on (the default), the geometric figure will move through three-dimensional space, bouncing off invisible walls that are perfectly elastic and frictionless.  There is continuous rotation about two different axes, as well as translational motion in all three dimensions.  If Free Running is toggled off, you may use the 'A' and 'R' keys to zoom the images away from you or return them toward you.  Also rotation through two degrees of freedom may be accomplished by using the up and down cursor keys to tilt the image about an horizontal axis, and left and right cursor keys to tilt it about a second axis which is initially perpendicular to the first axis.  This may be confusing to control with only the two degrees of freedom, so practice is required.

@endnode

@node Show_Walls "Show Walls"

The Show Walls option is off by default.  When it is toggled on, the edges of the invisible walls will be made visible.  This results in the addition of twelve additional lines to the drawing, so this may slow the animation in the Free Running mode.  How much will depend on the speed of your computer, what other tasks are running, and whether or not Constant Rate has been selected.

@endnode

@node Constant_Rate "Constant Rate"

The Constant Rate option is by default on.  Basically, the graphics function WaitTOF is used to be certain that the drawing of the next frame will not be started until the raster is near the bottom of the screen.  The intent is to keep the frame rate near a constant rate consistent with the vertical refresh (depending on the viewing mode), thereby reducing flicker.  This would be 15, 30 or perhaps 60 frames per second if using 60 Hz as the vertical refresh rate.  The success of this approach of course, depends not only on the speed of the computer, but also the number of line segments being displayed.  Note that the Constant Rate option is not used, if Free Running is not selected.

If you are using a third-party graphics card, such as the Picasso II or CyberVision64, there will be some synchronization, but only if the vertical frequency of your monitor is very close to that of the Amiga (60 Hz for NTSC, or 50 Hz for PAL).  A better result can be obtained by using CV64VBlankHack with the CyberVision64 card.  That is available as 'CV64BlankHack.lha' on AmiNet.  If you have CV64BlankHack in the same directory as StIco, it will be started by StIco automatically, but not if it is already running and not if it isn't in that directory.

@endnode

@node Sound "Sound"

The Sound option is by default on.  It is only available in the Free Running mode, and provides a 'clinking' sound when one of the vertices of the geometric object 'collides' with one of the invisible walls.  Note that the option to turn the sound off is provided to make StIco consistent with the MS-DOS Windows 3.1 version of StIco.  That was provided so that if audio software (rather than hardware) was generating the sound, it wouldn't slow down the animation.

@endnode

@node REVERSE_VIDEO "Reverse Video"

The normal method of display for StIco is to have a dark background with the geometric object drawn in a light color.  This gives the illusion of the object floating in the 'darkness of space'.  The reverse video provides a bright background with dark lines used to draw the object.  These modes can be most easily be 'toggled' back and forth using the Right-Amiga V command key combination.

Note that @{b} even @{ub} if you are only using a four color workbench, each \link "instance" "Instance" of StIco can independently be normal or reverse video.

@endnode

@node OTHER_PALETTE "Other Palette"

The default palette for StIco uses a black background with a red image for the left eye (which appears dark through the blue lens), a blue image for the right eye, and magenta for the intersection of the two.  This is the same default palette that is used in the Windows 3.1 version of StIco.  The reverse video mode uses a magenta background, with the colors for the left and right eyes reversed, and the intersection of any two colors displayed as black.  Note that I have been unable to provide a proper intersection of the two colors in Windows 3.1.  It is probable that the default palette will be required if you're running 'Productivity Mode' on your Amiga.

The alternate palette uses a dark grey-green background, with red for the left eye, greenish for right eye, and orangish for the intersection.  I usually find the reverse video of this palette easiest on my eyes.

These two palettes can be most easily be switched by using the Right-Amiga X command key combination.

Note that if you are only using 16 or more colors for your workbench, each @{"instance" link Instance} of StIco can independently choose its palette.

@endnode

@node WORKBENCH_COLORS "Workbench Colors"

If you're using less than 16 colors for your workbench, you have the option of toggling back and forth between the special palette and the workbench colors by using Right-Amiga T or selecting this menu item at any time.  You will find this especially useful if you are running a four-color Workbench.  In all cases, the original workbench colors are restored when the program StIco is terminated.  Note that the 'Reverse Video' and 'Other Palette' checkmarks won't be changed when 'Workbench Colors' is selected, but the checkmarks will be ignored.

@endnode

@node Eyes "Adjusting Eye Spacing"

Eye Spacing refers to the assumed distance between the user's eyes in pixels.  The default is 76 pixels, and this works well for me.  However, this assumes a certain screen resolution and viewing distance.  To increase the Eye Spacing, click on the number in the topmost box.  If you want to decrease spacing, toggle the sign in the second box.  If you don't have the 3D glasses, you can just 'Set the spacing to zero', so that StIco acts very similar to the original 'Ico' program.  Since the bit plane masking needed to generate the proper colors for viewing with the red-blue glasses isn't practical with more than 8-bit color, if you are using workbench with more than 8-bit color, the spacing is automatically set to 0.  'Save as New Default' is not (and may not be) implemented.  'Restore Default' sets the spacing back to 76 pixels, and of course, 'Use' lets the animation proceed.  If you drag the 'Adjust Eye Spacing' window aside, you'll be able to see the apparent depth change as you make your adjustments.


@endnode

@node UPDATE_TIMING "Update Timing"

Timing information can be obtained by pressing the 'U' key whenever an animation is progressing (whether or not in the 'Free Running' mode).  This is accomplished by reading the system time whenever a menu selection is made, and then reading the time again when the Update Timing selection is made.  The elapsed time is used to calculate the average frame rate during the animation sequence.  Note that if the Free Running option is not on, frame rate will be very low, as a new frame is only drawn in that case if one of the appropriate keys has been pressed.

This timing feature is provided so that you can do comparisons of the graphics speed of your computer in different display modes (or different number of Workbench colors, or against other computers.  I've found that there is a significant reduction in speed when switching to an eight or sixteen color workbench on my A3000.

When the selection has been made, a small window will be brought forward (if hidden) which displays the total number of frames generated, as well as the average frame rate over the most recent animation sequence.
The number of frames is displayed as a decimal integer, and the frame rate is displayed to the nearest one-hundredth of a frame per second.  The current animation will continue in the background until another selection is
made.
Note that for short time intervals, although the average frame rate is reasonably accurate it won't necessarily be indicative of the speed of your system.  Of course, the measured rate will depend upon what other tasks are running as well as the speed of your system.

@endnode

@node Instance "Multiple Instances"

I've borrowed the term "Multiple Instances" from Microsoft Windows to indicate that StIco is being executed more than one time.  Of course, multitasking is something the Amiga has been able to do from it's introduction in 1985.

@endnode

